{"title_page": "Neverending Past", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Neverending Past\n| image          = Neverending Past.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Andro Martinovic]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[Lazar Ristovski]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|2018|9|1|[[Montreal World Film Festival|Montreal]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 77 minutes\n| country        = Montenegro\n| language       = Montenegrin\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''Neverending Past''''' ({{lang-cnr|'''Izme\u0111u dana i no\u0107i'''}}) is a 2018 Montenegrin [[drama film|drama]] [[anthology film]] directed by [[Andro Martinovic]]. It was selected as the Montenegrin entry for the [[Academy Award for Best International Feature Film|Best International Feature Film]] at the [[92nd Academy Awards]], but it was not nominated.<ref name=\"Montenegro\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdm.me/kultura/film-izmedu-dana-i-noci-crnogorski-kandidat-za-nagradu-oskar-u-2019-godini/ |title=Film Izme\u0111u dana i no\u0107i crnogorski kandidat za nagradu Oskar u 2019. godini |work=Cafe del Montenegro |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/montenegro-picks-neverending-past-international-film-oscars-2020-1240336 |title=Oscars: Montenegro Selects 'Neverending Past' for International Feature Film Category |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Vladimir |last=Kozlov |accessdate=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThree stories examine relationships of fathers and sons. They span three eras: near the end of [[World War II]], during the fall of the [[Berlin Wall]], and in the early 1990s after the [[breakup of Yugoslavia]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Lazar Ristovski]]\n* [[Tihomir Stanic]]\n* Srdjan Grahovac\n* Marko Bacovic\n* Jovan Krivokapic\n* [[Dubravka Drakic]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 92nd Academy Awards for Best International Feature Film]]\n* [[List of Montenegrin submissions for the Academy Award for Best International Feature Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|4792240|Neverending Past}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neverending Past}}\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2018 drama films]]\n[[Category:Montenegrin films]]\n[[Category:Serbian-language films]]\n[[Category:Anthology films]]\n{{Montenegro-film-stub}}\n{{2010s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Neverending Past\n| image          = Neverending Past.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Andro Martinovic]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[Lazar Ristovski]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|2018|9|1|[[Montreal World Film Festival|Montreal]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 77 minutes\n| country        = Montenegro\n| language       = Montenegrin\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''Neverending Past''''' ({{lang-cnr|'''Izme\u0111u dana i no\u0107i'''}}) is a 2018 Montenegrin [[drama film|drama]] [[anthology film]] directed by [[Andro Martinovic]]. It was selected as the Montenegrin entry for the [[Academy Award for Best International Feature Film|Best International Feature Film]] at the [[92nd Academy Awards]], but it was not nominated.<ref name=\"Montenegro\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdm.me/kultura/film-izmedu-dana-i-noci-crnogorski-kandidat-za-nagradu-oskar-u-2019-godini/ |title=Film Izme\u0111u dana i no\u0107i crnogorski kandidat za nagradu Oskar u 2019. godini |work=Cafe del Montenegro |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/montenegro-picks-neverending-past-international-film-oscars-2020-1240336 |title=Oscars: Montenegro Selects 'Neverending Past' for International Feature Film Category |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Vladimir |last=Kozlov |accessdate=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThree stories examine relationships of fathers and sons. They span three eras: near the end of [[World War II]], during the fall of the [[Berlin Wall]], and in the early 1990s after the [[breakup of Yugoslavia]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Lazar Ristovski]]\n* [[Tihomir Stanic]]\n* Srdjan Grahovac\n* Marko Bacovic\n* Jovan Krivokapic\n* [[Dubravka Drakic]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 92nd Academy Awards for Best International Feature Film]]\n* [[List of Montenegrin submissions for the Academy Award for Best International Feature Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|4792240|Neverending Past}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neverending Past}}\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2018 drama films]]\n[[Category:Montenegrin films]]\n[[Category:Serbian-language films]]\n[[Category:Anthology films]]\n{{Montenegro-film-stub}}\n{{2010s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neverending_Past"}
{"title_page": "Razing of Friesoythe", "text_new": "{{short description|World War II battle and war crime}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=September 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Razing of Friesoythe\n| partof      = [[Western Front (World War II)|Western Front]], World War II\n| image       = File:Captured German flag, Friesoythe, Germany, 16 April 1945.jpg\n|image_size = 300px\n| caption     = Canadian soldiers with a [[Hitler Youth]] flag at Friesoythe on 16 April 1945\n| date        = 13\u201314 April 1945\n| place       = [[Friesoythe]]\n| coordinates =\n| map_type    =\n| map_relief  =\n| latitude    =\n| longitude   =\n| map_size    =\n| map_marksize =\n| map_caption =\n| map_label   =\n| territory   =\n| result      = Canadian victory\n* Destruction of the town\n| status      =\n| combatants_header =\n| combatant1  = {{flag|Canada|1921}}\n| combatant2  = {{flag|Nazi Germany|name=Germany}}\n| commander1  = {{flagicon|Canada|1921}} [[Christopher Vokes]]<br>{{flagicon|Canada|1921}} Fred Wigle\n| commander2  = Unknown\n| units1      = Part of [[4th Canadian (Armoured) Division]]\n| units2      = Part of [[7th Parachute Division (Germany)|7th&nbsp;German Parachute Division]]\n| strength1   = Three battalions\n| strength2   = 200\u2013500 men\n| casualties1 = Unknown\n| casualties2 = Unknown\n| casualties3 =\n| notes       =\n| campaignbox =\n{{Campaignbox Central Europe}}\n{{Campaignbox Western Europe (1944-1945)}}\n}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = Friesoythe\n| pushpin_map            = Lower Saxony\n| pushpin_label_position = right\n| pushpin_map_alt        =\n| coordinates            = {{coord|53|01|14|N|07|51|31|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| map_caption            = Friesoythe within Lower Saxony, Germany\n}}\n\nThe '''Razing of Friesoythe''' was a war crime that took place on 14&nbsp;April 1945 during the [[Western Allied invasion of Germany|Western Allies' invasion of Germany]] towards the end of World War II. The [[4th Canadian (Armoured) Division]] attacked the German-held town of [[Friesoythe]] and one of its [[battalion]]s, [[Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada (Princess Louise's)|The Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada]], captured it.\n\nDuring the fighting the battalion's commander was killed by a German soldier, but it was incorrectly rumoured that he had been killed by a civilian. Under this mistaken belief, the division's commander, [[Major General|Major-General]] [[Christopher Vokes]], ordered that the town be razed in [[Reprisal|retaliation]] and it was substantially destroyed. Twenty German civilians died in Friesoythe and the surrounding area during the two days of fighting and its aftermath. Similar, if usually less extreme, events occurred elsewhere in Germany as the Allies advanced in the closing weeks of the war.\n\nThe rubble of the town was used to fill craters in local roads to make them passable for the division's tanks and heavy vehicles. A few days earlier, the division had destroyed the centre of [[S\u00f6gel]] in another reprisal and also used the rubble to make the roads passable. Little official notice was taken of the incident and the [[Official History of the Canadian Army in the Second World War|Canadian Army official history]] glosses over it. It is covered in the regimental histories of the units involved and several accounts of the campaign. Forty years later, Vokes wrote in his autobiography that he had \"no great remorse over the elimination of Friesoythe\".\n\n==Context==\n===Allied tactics===\nBy September 1944, the [[Allies of World War II|Western Allies]] had reached [[Nazi Germany|Germany's]] western border,{{sfn|Ambrose|1997|p=117}} and by the end of October had [[Battle of Aachen|captured Aachen]], the first major German city to fall to them.{{sfn|Hastings|2004|pp=106\u2013107}} Over the following six months they overran much of western Germany. In November the [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Expeditionary Force]] (SHAEF) publicly stated that the forces of the Western Allies would strictly adhere to international law in respect of their treatment of civilians.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=256}} However, SHAEF's manual ''Combating the Guerrilla'' stated that there were circumstances where commanders could take \"stern measures\" against civilians as a [[reprisal|rapid response]] to guerrilla attacks, although this was in breach of the [[Hague Conventions of 1899 and 1907|Hague Conventions]].{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=256}}\n\nThe frequency and nature of retaliatory actions differed between national contingents within the Western Allied forces.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=257}} Following SHAEF's policy, [[United States Army]] forces destroyed German buildings on several occasions, sometimes entire villages, and took other measures against German civilians. French troops took a similar, if more rigorous, approach to that of the Americans.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|pp=258\u2013259}} The British commanders disapproved of retaliations against civilians, and British troops carried out few reprisals.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=257}}\n\nThe [[First Canadian Army]] served in the predominately British [[21st Army Group]], and more frequently retaliated against German civilians than the British.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=257}} The commander of [[4th Canadian Division|4th&nbsp;Canadian (Armoured) Division]], Major-General [[Christopher Vokes]], believed that destroying property was the most appropriate way of responding to resistance by German civilians. The division carried out actions against German property more often than any other Canadian formation.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|pp=258\u2013259}}\n\n[[Red Army|Soviet forces]] conducted retaliatory actions much more frequently than their Western Allies. The [[Soviet Union]]'s leadership was concerned about the threat of a [[Werwolf|German resistance movement]], and Soviet forces killed, raped and imprisoned large numbers of local civilians and destroyed property following guerrilla attacks.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|pp=268\u2013270}}\n\n===Allied attitudes===\n\nThe attitude towards the Germans throughout the Allied ranks was harsh. There was frustration at their continued resistance in a clearly hopeless cause, anger at the casualties they inflicted when the war was widely, and correctly, perceived to be almost over, and a general feeling that severe, even ruthless, treatment of German soldiers and civilians was justified.{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|p=597}} On 15&nbsp;April the British reached [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp]], where the inmates had been reduced to cannibalism.{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|p=599}} The historian [[Rick Atkinson]] wrote that \"the revelations of April&nbsp;... sparked enduring outrage\".{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|p=604}}\n\nThis was the case at all levels. An American officer wrote \"The attitude of higher command seemed to be that these people&nbsp;... should be made to feel the full significance of war and what their troops had done to other people.\"{{sfn|Hastings|2004|pp=493\u2013494}} The US general [[George Patton]] wrote in his diary \"In hundreds of villages&nbsp;... most of the houses are heaps of stone&nbsp;... I did most of it.\" When a [[sniper]] fired at one of his officers, he ordered several German houses to be burnt.{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|p=568}} When the commander of US [[3rd Armored Division (United States)|3rd Armored Division]] was killed in action {{convert|150|mi|km|disp=flip}} inside Germany on 30&nbsp;March, several villages were razed by his irate troops, captured wounded Germans were shot on the spot and at least 45&nbsp;Germans were executed after surrendering.{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|pp=581\u2013582}} An artillery officer wrote home in April \"we should fire about a thousand rounds into every [German] town. Do them good\".{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|p=598}} At least one British battalion refused to take [[Waffen-SS]] prisoners, shooting those who surrendered; an officer of the battalion blamed this on SS \"truculence\".{{sfn|Hastings|2004|p=499}} A British battalion commander summed up the risk-averse attitude within his unit: \"At this stage of the war, no one was very keen to earn medals.\"{{sfn|Hastings|2004|p=492}} A British pilot wrote: \"It seemed a stupid time to die.\"{{sfn|Hastings|2004|p=492}} A British [[corporal]] spoke for many when he wrote \"Why don't the silly bastards give up?\"{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|p=597}} Some divisions had suffered their last fatality by mid-April.{{sfn|Hastings|2004|p=500}} The historian [[Max Hastings]] wrote \"The final Anglo-American drive across Germany offered ... many foolish little battles which wasted men's lives\".{{sfn|Hastings|2004|p=491}}\n\n===Battle for S\u00f6gel===\n[[File:Moncel and Vokes.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|right|alt=Major-General Christopher Vokes in discussion with Brigadier Robert Moncel standing in a street in S\u00f6gel on 10&nbsp;April 1945|{{center|Major-General [[Christopher Vokes]] (right) with Brigadier [[Robert Moncel]] at S\u00f6gel on 10 April 1945.}}]]\nIn early April 1945 the 4th&nbsp;Canadian (Armoured) Division, as part of [[II&nbsp;Canadian Corps]], moved out of the eastern Netherlands in the wake of the Allied crossing of the [[Rhine]] in [[Operation Plunder]]. The Canadian official history describes the circumstances as buoyant as it was recognized that the end of World War II in Europe was close.{{sfn|Stacey|1960|p=527}} On 4&nbsp;April, [[Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada (Princess Louise's)|The Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada]], part of the [[10th&nbsp;Canadian Infantry Brigade]], one of two [[brigades]] in the division,{{#tag:ref|The other battalions in the brigade were: [[The Lincoln and Welland Regiment]]; and [[The Algonquin Regiment]].{{sfn|Canadian Soldier|2019}}|group=Note}} made an assault crossing of the [[Ems (river)|Ems]] river and captured the town of [[Meppen]], suffering only one casualty. German prisoners included several 17-year-old youths with less than eight weeks of military experience.{{sfn|Stacey|1960|p=557}}\n\nThe division advanced a further {{convert|25|km}} to S\u00f6gel, which the 1st&nbsp;Battalion of [[Lake Superior Regiment|The Lake Superior Regiment (Motor)]]{{#tag:ref|The Lake Superior Regiment (Motor) was part of [[4th Canadian Armoured Brigade]] which also included: 21st Armoured Regiment ([[The Governor General's Foot Guards]]); 22nd&nbsp;Armoured Regiment ([[The Canadian Grenadier Guards]]); and 28th&nbsp;Armoured Regiment ([[The British Columbia Regiment]]).{{sfn|Canadian Soldier|2019}}|group=Note}} captured on 9&nbsp;April. The following day it repulsed several German counter-attacks before the town was declared cleared.{{sfn|Williams|1988|p=276}}{{sfn|Stacey|1960|p=558}} Some German civilians joined the fighting and were believed to have killed several Canadian soldiers. Vokes, believing the civilians needed to be taught a lesson, ordered the destruction of the centre of the town.{{sfn|Morton|2016|}} This was accomplished with several truckloads of dynamite. Vokes was aware that these actions violated the Hague Conventions and took care not to issue written instructions.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|pp=258\u2013259}} Soldiers of the division started referring to Vokes as \"The Sod of S\u00f6gel\".{{sfn|Foster|2000|page=437}} The Canadian Army official history states: {{quote|Investigation established that German civilians had taken part in this fighting and had been responsible for the loss of Canadian lives. Accordingly, as a [[reprisal]] and a warning, several houses in the centre of S\u00f6gel were ordered destroyed by the engineers to provide rubble.{{sfn|Stacey|1960|p=558}}}}\n\n==Battle for Friesoythe==\n\nThe Canadian advance continued across the [[Westphalian Lowland]], reaching the outskirts of Friesoythe, a strategic crossroads, on 13&nbsp;April. As it was early spring, the ground was sodden and heavy vehicles could not operate off the main roads.{{sfn|Stacey|1960|p=558}} This made Friesoythe, {{convert|20|mi|km|disp=flip}} west of [[Oldenburg]], on the River [[Soeste]], a potential bottleneck. If the Germans were to hold it, the bulk of the Canadians would be unable to continue their advance.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=305}} Most of the population of 4,000 had evacuated to the countryside on 11\u201312 April.{{#tag:ref|The Friesoythe Amtsgericht, or District Court, was closed on 11&nbsp; April. If the District Court ceased to function on 11&nbsp;April 1945, the evacuation of the bulk of the civilian population probably took place between 11&nbsp;and 12&nbsp;April. This was clearly a German initiative.{{sfn|Cloppenburg|2003|pp=165, 189}}{{sfn|Brockhaus|1996|p=730}}|group=Note}} Several hundred paratroopers from Battalion Raabe of the German [[7th Parachute Division (Germany)|7th&nbsp;Parachute Division]] and anti-tank guns defended the town.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=305}}{{sfn|Sirluck|1945|}} The paratroopers repelled an attack by the Lake Superior Regiment, which suffered several killed and wounded; German casualties are unknown.{{sfn|Marsh|2015|}}\n\nVokes ordered the resumption of the attack by the 1st&nbsp;Battalion, The Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders (Princess Louise's), commanded by [[Lieutenant-colonel (Canada)|Lieutenant-Colonel]] Frederick Wigle. The Argylls conducted a flanking night march and launched a dawn assault on 14&nbsp;April. The attack met only scattered resistance from a disorganized garrison, and the Argylls secured the town by 10:30. During the confused fighting, approximately 50&nbsp;German soldiers{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=257}} caught Wigle's tactical headquarters by surprise at around 08:30. A firefight broke out, resulting in the death of Wigle and several other soldiers. A rumour circulated that a local civilian had shot Wigle.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=308}}{{sfn|A&SHC archive|1945}}{{sfn|Fraser|1996|p=431}}\n\n===Destruction of Friesoythe===\nVokes was furious when he heard of Wigle's death. He wrote in his autobiography that \"a first-rate officer of mine, for whom I had a special regard and affection, and in whom I had a particular professional interest because of his talent for command, was killed. Not merely killed, it was reported to me, but sniped in the back\". Vokes wrote, \"I summoned my {{Abbr|GSO1|general staff officer}}... 'Mac,' I roared at him, 'I'm going to raze that goddam town. Tell 'em we're going to level the fucking place. Get the people the hell out of their houses first.{{'\"}}{{sfn|Foster|2000|page=437}}{{sfn|Vokes|1985|pages=194\u2013195}} Vokes's [[Staff_(military)#British_and_Commonwealth_staff|GSO1 (head of the operations staff)]], Lieutenant-Colonel Mackenzie Robinson, obeyed but convinced him to not put this order in writing or issue a proclamation to the local civilians.{{sfn|Foster|2000|page=437}}{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|pp=259, 295}} Hastings writes that the earlier incident at S\u00f6gel contributed to Vokes's fury.{{sfn|Hastings|2004|p=500}}\n\nThe Argylls had spontaneously begun to burn Friesoythe in reprisal for the death of their commander.{{sfn|Fraser|1996|pp=435\u2013437}} After Vokes had issued his order, the town was systematically set on fire with [[flamethrowers]] mounted on [[Universal Carrier|Wasp Carriers]]. In the side streets, soldiers threw petrol containers into buildings and ignited them with [[White phosphorus munitions|phosphorus grenades]]. The attack continued for over eight hours and Friesoythe was almost totally destroyed.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=308}} As the commanding officer of the 1st&nbsp;Battalion, [[The Algonquin Regiment]] later wrote, \"the raging Highlanders cleared the remainder of that town as no town has been cleared for centuries, we venture to say\".{{sfn|Cassidy|1948|p=307}} The war diary of the 4th&nbsp;Canadian Armoured Brigade records, \"when darkness fell Friesoythe was a reasonable facsimile of Dante's Inferno\".{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=309}}\n\nThe Canadian official history states that Friesoythe \"was set on fire in a mistaken reprisal\".{{sfn|Stacey|1960|p=722}} The rubble was used to reinforce the local roads for the division's tanks and heavy transport, which had been unable to move up due to the main roads near the town being badly cratered, and the smaller roads being inadequate to stand their weight.{{sfn|Rogers|1989|p=259}}{{sfn|Granatstein|2010|p=16}}\n\n===Civilian casualties and damage===\nDuring the fighting around Friesoythe and its aftermath, ten civilians from the town and another ten from the surrounding villages were killed.{{sfn|Stadt Friesoythe|2018}} There were reports of civilians lying dead in the streets.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=308}} According to one German assessment, 85\u201390 per cent of the town was destroyed during the reprisal.{{sfn|Cloppenburg|2003|p=189}} The {{Lang|de|Brockhaus Enzyklopaedie}} estimates the destruction to have been as high as 90 per cent. The town's website records that of 381{{nbsp}}houses in the town proper, 231{{nbsp}}were destroyed and another 30&nbsp;badly damaged.{{sfn|Stadt Friesoythe|2018}} A few days later, a Canadian nurse wrote home that the [[convent]] on the edge of town was the only building left standing.{{sfn|Hibbert|1985|p=84}} In the suburb of Altenoythe, 120{{nbsp}}houses and 110{{nbsp}}other buildings were destroyed.{{sfn|Stadt Friesoythe|2018}} In 2010, the author Mark Zuehlke suggested that, \"Not all of Friesoythe was burnt, but its centre was destroyed\".{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=309}}\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n{{Quote box|width=20em|align=left|quote=You should know our soldiers were kind to the children of our enemies, and kind to those in adversity. And they were, on the whole, great ambassadors for Canada.|source=Major-General Christopher Vokes in his autobiography{{sfn|Vokes|1985|p=x}}}}The Argyll's war diary made no mention of their afternoon's activity, noting in passing that \"many fires were raging\". There is no record of the deliberate destruction at division, corps or army level.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=309}} The war diary of the division's 8th&nbsp;Anti-Aircraft Regiment records \"the Argylls were attacked in that town yesterday by German forces assisted by civilians and today the whole town is being systematically razed. A stern atonement&nbsp;...\"{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=309}} The 1st&nbsp;Battalion, The Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders (Princess Louise's) were awarded the [[battle honour]] \"Friesoythe\", as were the 1st&nbsp;Battalion, The Lake Superior Regiment (Motor) and the 1st&nbsp;Battalion, [[The Lincoln and Welland Regiment]].{{sfn|Canadian Forces Heritage|2017}}\n\nOn 16&nbsp;April The Lincoln and Welland Regiment attacked [[Garrel]], {{convert|10|miles|km|disp=flip}} south-west of Friesoythe. After a German act of [[perfidy]]{{snd}}the mayor surrendered the town but the first tank to enter was destroyed by a [[Panzerfaust]]{{snd}}the battalion commander, Wigle's brother-in-law, ordered that \"every building which did not show a white flag be fired\".{{sfn|L&WR archive|1945}} Before it could be carried out, the order was countermanded and the village was spared.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=312}} A Canadian force was also authorized to burn down the village of [[Mittelsten]] following what the historian Perry Briddiscombe calls \"an unnamed transgression\". They were talked out of this by a Canadian engineer unit as Mittelsten's civilians were running an army sawmill.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=258}}\n\n===Post-war===\nIn early 1946 Vokes heard an appeal against the death sentence of [[Kurt Meyer]], a convicted German war criminal. Referring to his discussions about this Vokes said to the [[Vincent Massey|Canadian High Commissioner]] in London, \"I told them of S\u00f6gel and Friesoythe and of the prisoners and civilians that my troops had killed in Italy and Northwest Europe\".{{sfn|Foster|2000|page=437}} Vokes [[commutation of sentence|commuted]] the sentence to life imprisonment saying, \"There isn't a general or colonel on the Allied side that I know of who hasn't said, 'Well, this time we don't want any prisoners{{'}}\".{{sfn|Brode|1997|p=105}}\n\nThe Canadian Army official historian, Colonel [[Charles Perry Stacey|Charles Stacey]], visited Friesoythe on 15&nbsp;April. He wrote in the Canadian Army official history, which was published in 1960, that \"there is no record of how this [destruction] came about\".{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|p=309}}{{sfn|Stacey|1960|pp=558, 722}} Responding to this, the historian Mark Zuehlke wrote that there were records of the events in the war diaries of several units, but that he did not believe Stacey's vagueness was an attempt at a cover-up.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|p=309}} In his 1982 memoirs Stacey expanded upon the official history to comment that the only time he saw what could be considered a [[war crime]] committed by Canadian soldiers{{#tag:ref|The [[Hague Conventions of 1899 and 1907|1907 Convention Respecting the Laws and Customs of War on Land]] (Hague{{nbsp}}IV), Article{{nbsp}}23, prohibits acts that \"destroy or seize the enemy's property, unless such destruction or seizure be imperatively demanded by the necessities of war.\"{{sfn|ICRC|1907}}|group=Note}} was when\n{{quote|... at Friesoythe, the Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada&nbsp;... lost their popular commanding officer&nbsp;... as a result a great part of the town of Friesoythe was set on fire in a mistaken reprisal. This unfortunate episode only came to my notice and thus got into the pages of history because I was in Friesoythe at the time and saw people being turned out of their houses and the houses burned. How painfully easy it is for the business of \"reprisals\" to get out of hand!{{sfn|Stacey|1982|pp=163\u2013164}}}}\n\nVokes commented in his autobiography, written forty years after the event, that he had \"[a] feeling of no great remorse over the elimination of Friesoythe. Be that as it may.\"{{sfn|Morton|2016}}{{sfn|Foster|2000|page=437}} This position may have been motivated by a continued belief that the retaliatory actions were justified.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=295}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Allied war crimes during World War II]]\n* [[List of war crimes]]\n\n==Notes, citations and sources==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Ambrose | first = Stephen E. | title = Citizen Soldiers: The U.S. Army From the Normandy Beaches to the Bulge to the Surrender of Germany | publisher = [[Simon & Schuster]] | year = 1997 | location = New York City, New York | isbn = 0-684-815257 | url = https://archive.org/details/citizensoldiers000ambr|ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book\n|last=\n|first=\n|date=\n|id= RG 24, v. 15,005\n|title=Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada War Diary\n|url=\n|location=Ottawa, ON, Canada\n|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]\n|pages=10\u201311\n|isbn=\n|author-link=\n|ref={{sfnRef|A&SHC archive|1945}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Atkinson|first=Rick|authorlink=Rick Atkinson|title=The Guns at Last Light|location=Great Britain|publisher=[[Abacus]]|date=2015|isbn=978-0-349-14048-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Briddiscombe |first1=Perry |title=Werwolf! : The History of the National Socialist Guerrilla Movement, 1944\u20131946 |date=1998 |publisher=[[University of Toronto Press]] |location=Toronto |isbn=978-0-8020-0862-6 |ref=harv |url=https://archive.org/details/werwolfhistoryof00bidd }}\n* {{Cite book |title=[[Brockhaus Enzyklop\u00e4die|Die Enzyklop\u00e4die]], 20. Aufl. V. 7 |publisher=Brockhaus |year=1996 |isbn= |location=Leipzig |ref=CITEREFBrockhaus1996}}\n* {{cite book\n  |first=Patrick\n  |last=Brode\n  |title=Casual Slaughters and Accidental Judgements: Canadian War Crimes Prosecutions, 1944\u20131948\n  |year=1997\n|location=Toronto; Buffalo\n|publisher=For Osgoode Society for Canadian Legal History by University of Toronto Press\n  |isbn=08020-4204-X\n  |ref=harv\n  |url=https://archive.org/details/casualslaughters0000brod\n  }}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.cmp-cpm.forces.gc.ca/dhh-dhp/his/ol-lo/vol-tom-3/par2/doc/ir-ri.pdf|title=''The Insignia and Linages of the Canadian Forces''. Volume 3, Part Two. \"Infantry Regiments\"|last=|first=|date=13 August 2018|website=A Canadian Forces Heritage Publication|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206053149/http://www.cmp-cpm.forces.gc.ca/dhh-dhp/his/ol-lo/vol-tom-3/par2/doc/ir-ri.pdf|archive-date=6 December 2017|access-date=|ref={{sfnRef|Canadian Forces Heritage|2017}}}}\n{{cite web | url=http://www.canadiansoldiers.com/organization/fieldforces/casf/4thdivision.htm | title=4th Canadian (Armoured) Division | publisher=Canadian Soldier | accessdate=21 November 2019|ref={{sfnRef|Canadian Soldier|2019}}}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Warpath; the Story of the Algonquin Regiment, 1939\u20131945 |last=Cassidy |first=G. L. |publisher=[[Ryerson Press]] |year=1948 |oclc=937425850 |location=Toronto |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Die Stadt Friesoythe im zwanzigsten Jahrhundert |trans-title=The town of Friesoythe in the twentieth century) |last=Cloppenburg |first=Ferdinand |location=Friesoythe |publisher=Schepers |year=2003 |language=German |isbn= 3-00-012759-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Meeting of Generals |last=Foster |first=Tony |publisher=[[iUniverse]] |year=2000 |isbn=978-0-595-13750-3 |location=San Jose; New York |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Black Yesterdays; the Argylls' War |last=Fraser |first=Robert L. |publisher=Argyll Regimental Foundation |year=1996 |isbn=978-0-9681380-0-7 |location=Hamilton |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.friesoythe.de/portal/seiten/chronik-1930-bis-1948-907000038-23250.html?rubrik=907000002|title=Chronik \u2013 1930 bis 1948 {{!}} Stadt Friesoythe|last=Friesoythe|access-date=14 January 2018|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911044805/https://www.friesoythe.de/portal/seiten/chronik-1930-bis-1948-907000038-23250.html?rubrik=907000002|archive-date=11 September 2018|ref={{sfnRef|Stadt Friesoythe|2018}}}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.macdonaldlaurier.ca/files/pdf/The_Roads_To_Victory.pdf|title=Legion Magazine|date=May\u2013June 2010|website=|page=16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127084422/https://www.macdonaldlaurier.ca/files/pdf/The_Roads_To_Victory.pdf|archive-date=27 January 2018|first=J.L. |last=Granatstein|author-link= Jack Granatstein|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|last=Hastings\n|first=Max\n|date=2004\n|title=Armageddon: the Battle for Germany 1944\u201345\n|url=\n|location=London\n|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]\n|page=\n|isbn=0-333-90836-8\n|author-link=Max Hastings\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Fragments of War: Stories from Survivors of World War II |last=Hibbert |first=Joyce |year=1985 |publisher=[[Dundurn Press]] |isbn=978-0-919670-95-2 |location=Toronto |ref=harv |url=https://archive.org/details/fragmentsofwarst0000hibb }}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://ihl-databases.icrc.org/applic/ihl/ihl.nsf/0/1d1726425f6955aec125641e0038bfd6|title=Convention (IV) respecting the Laws and Customs of War on Land and its annex: Regulations concerning the Laws and Customs of War on Land|website=ihl-databases.icrc.org|language=en-us|access-date=26 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127202410/https://ihl-databases.icrc.org/applic/ihl/ihl.nsf/0/1d1726425f6955aec125641e0038bfd6|archive-date=27 January 2018|ref={{sfnRef|ICRC|1907}}}}\n* {{cite book |title=Lincoln and Welland Regiment War Diary, April 1945 |id=RG24/8 |publisher=Library and Archives Canada |number=8|location=Ottawa, ON, Canada|ref={{sfnRef|L&WR archive|1945}}}}\n* {{Cite web|title=One More River to Cross: The Canadians in Holland|last=Marsh|first=James H.|work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/one-more-river-to-cross-the-canadians-in-holland-feature/ |access-date=13 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180329212709/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/one-more-river-to-cross-the-canadians-in-holland-feature/|archive-date=29 March 2018|ref=harv|year=2015 |orig-year=2013}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/christopher-vokes/ |title=Christopher Vokes |last=Morton |first=Desmond |work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |access-date=24 January 2018 |year=2016 |orig-year=2008 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=History of The Lincoln and Welland Regiment |last=Rogers |first=R. L. |publisher=Lincoln and Welland Regiment, Canadian Army |year=1989 |location=Ottawa |oclc=13090416 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Sirluck |first=E. |title=Intelligence Report, War Diary, General Staff, 4th Canadian Armoured Division, 1 April 1945{{snd}}30 April 1945.&nbsp;Appendix 38 |date=14 April 1945|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|location=RG 24, vol. no. 13794|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |series=[[Official History of the Canadian Army in the Second World War]] |title=The Victory Campaign: The Operations in North-west Europe 1944\u201345 |volume=III |url=http://epe.lac-bac.gc.ca/100/200/301/dhh-dhp/official_history_cdn_army_ww2/D2-503E.pdf |last=Stacey |first=Charles Perry|publisher=[[Queen's Printer]] |year=1960 |location=Ottawa |oclc=317352926 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=A Date With History |last=Stacey |first=Charles Perry |publisher=Deneau |year=1982 |isbn=978-0-88879-086-6 |location=Ottawa |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_0888791143 }}\n* {{Cite book |title=Vokes: My Story |last=Vokes |first=Chris |publisher=[[Gallery Books]] |year=1985 |isbn=978-0-9692109-0-0 |location=Ottawa |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=The Long Left Flank: the Hard Fought Way to the Reich, 1944\u20131945 |last=Williams |first=Jeffery |year=1988 |publisher=[[Stoddart Publishing|Stoddart]] |isbn=978-0-7737-2194-4 |location=Toronto |oclc=25747884 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=On To Victory: The Canadian Liberation of the Netherlands |last=Zuehlke |first=Mark |publisher=[[Greystone Books]] |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-55365-430-8 |location=Vancouver |ref=harv}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Friesoythe, Razing of}}\n\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving Germany]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving Canada]]\n[[Category:1945 in Germany]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1945]]\n[[Category:April 1945 events]]\n[[Category:War crimes]]\n[[Category:Collective punishment]]\n[[Category:World War II crimes]]\n[[Category:Razed cities]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|World War II battle and war crime}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=September 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Razing of Friesoythe\n| partof      = [[Western Front (World War II)|Western Front]], World War II\n| image       = File:Captured German flag, Friesoythe, Germany, 16 April 1945.jpg\n|image_size = 300px\n| caption     = Canadian soldiers with a [[Hitler Youth]] flag at Friesoythe on 16 April 1945\n| date        = 13\u201314 April 1945\n| place       = [[Friesoythe]]\n| coordinates =\n| map_type    =\n| map_relief  =\n| latitude    =\n| longitude   =\n| map_size    =\n| map_marksize =\n| map_caption =\n| map_label   =\n| territory   =\n| result      = Canadian victory\n* Destruction of the town\n| status      =\n| combatants_header =\n| combatant1  = {{flag|Canada|1921}}\n| combatant2  = {{flag|Nazi Germany|name=Germany}}\n| commander1  = {{flagicon|Canada|1921}} [[Christopher Vokes]]<br>{{flagicon|Canada|1921}} Fred Wigle\n| commander2  = Unknown\n| units1      = Part of [[4th Canadian (Armoured) Division]]\n| units2      = Part of [[7th Parachute Division (Germany)|7th&nbsp;German Parachute Division]]\n| strength1   = Three battalions\n| strength2   = 200\u2013500 men\n| casualties1 = Unknown\n| casualties2 = Unknown\n| casualties3 =\n| notes       =\n| campaignbox =\n{{Campaignbox Central Europe}}\n{{Campaignbox Western Europe (1944-1945)}}\n}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = Friesoythe\n| pushpin_map            = Lower Saxony\n| pushpin_label_position = right\n| pushpin_map_alt        =\n| coordinates            = {{coord|53|01|14|N|07|51|31|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| map_caption            = Friesoythe within Lower Saxony, Germany\n}}\n\nThe '''Razing of Friesoythe''' took place on 14&nbsp;April 1945 during the [[Western Allied invasion of Germany|Western Allies' invasion of Germany]] towards the end of World War II. The [[4th Canadian (Armoured) Division]] attacked the German-held town of [[Friesoythe]] and one of its [[battalion]]s, [[Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada (Princess Louise's)|The Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada]], captured it.\n\nDuring the fighting the battalion's commander was killed by a German soldier, but it was incorrectly rumoured that he had been killed by a civilian. Under this mistaken belief, the division's commander, [[Major General|Major-General]] [[Christopher Vokes]], ordered that the town be razed in [[Reprisal|retaliation]] and it was substantially destroyed. Twenty German civilians died in Friesoythe and the surrounding area during the two days of fighting and its aftermath. Similar, if usually less extreme, events occurred elsewhere in Germany as the Allies advanced in the closing weeks of the war.\n\nThe rubble of the town was used to fill craters in local roads to make them passable for the division's tanks and heavy vehicles. A few days earlier, the division had destroyed the centre of [[S\u00f6gel]] in another reprisal and also used the rubble to make the roads passable. Little official notice was taken of the incident and the [[Official History of the Canadian Army in the Second World War|Canadian Army official history]] glosses over it. It is covered in the regimental histories of the units involved and several accounts of the campaign. Forty years later, Vokes wrote in his autobiography that he had \"no great remorse over the elimination of Friesoythe\".\n\n==Context==\n===Allied tactics===\nBy September 1944, the [[Allies of World War II|Western Allies]] had reached [[Nazi Germany|Germany's]] western border,{{sfn|Ambrose|1997|p=117}} and by the end of October had [[Battle of Aachen|captured Aachen]], the first major German city to fall to them.{{sfn|Hastings|2004|pp=106\u2013107}} Over the following six months they overran much of western Germany. In November the [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Expeditionary Force]] (SHAEF) publicly stated that the forces of the Western Allies would strictly adhere to international law in respect of their treatment of civilians.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=256}} However, SHAEF's manual ''Combating the Guerrilla'' stated that there were circumstances where commanders could take \"stern measures\" against civilians as a [[reprisal|rapid response]] to guerrilla attacks, although this was in breach of the [[Hague Conventions of 1899 and 1907|Hague Conventions]].{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=256}}\n\nThe frequency and nature of retaliatory actions differed between national contingents within the Western Allied forces.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=257}} Following SHAEF's policy, [[United States Army]] forces destroyed German buildings on several occasions, sometimes entire villages, and took other measures against German civilians. French troops took a similar, if more rigorous, approach to that of the Americans.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|pp=258\u2013259}} The British commanders disapproved of retaliations against civilians, and British troops carried out few reprisals.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=257}}\n\nThe [[First Canadian Army]] served in the predominately British [[21st Army Group]], and more frequently retaliated against German civilians than the British.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=257}} The commander of [[4th Canadian Division|4th&nbsp;Canadian (Armoured) Division]], Major-General [[Christopher Vokes]], believed that destroying property was the most appropriate way of responding to resistance by German civilians. The division carried out actions against German property more often than any other Canadian formation.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|pp=258\u2013259}}\n\n[[Red Army|Soviet forces]] conducted retaliatory actions much more frequently than their Western Allies. The [[Soviet Union]]'s leadership was concerned about the threat of a [[Werwolf|German resistance movement]], and Soviet forces killed, raped and imprisoned large numbers of local civilians and destroyed property following guerrilla attacks.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|pp=268\u2013270}}\n\n===Allied attitudes===\n\nThe attitude towards the Germans throughout the Allied ranks was harsh. There was frustration at their continued resistance in a clearly hopeless cause, anger at the casualties they inflicted when the war was widely, and correctly, perceived to be almost over, and a general feeling that severe, even ruthless, treatment of German soldiers and civilians was justified.{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|p=597}} On 15&nbsp;April the British reached [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp]], where the inmates had been reduced to cannibalism.{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|p=599}} The historian [[Rick Atkinson]] wrote that \"the revelations of April&nbsp;... sparked enduring outrage\".{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|p=604}}\n\nThis was the case at all levels. An American officer wrote \"The attitude of higher command seemed to be that these people&nbsp;... should be made to feel the full significance of war and what their troops had done to other people.\"{{sfn|Hastings|2004|pp=493\u2013494}} The US general [[George Patton]] wrote in his diary \"In hundreds of villages&nbsp;... most of the houses are heaps of stone&nbsp;... I did most of it.\" When a [[sniper]] fired at one of his officers, he ordered several German houses to be burnt.{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|p=568}} When the commander of US [[3rd Armored Division (United States)|3rd Armored Division]] was killed in action {{convert|150|mi|km|disp=flip}} inside Germany on 30&nbsp;March, several villages were razed by his irate troops, captured wounded Germans were shot on the spot and at least 45&nbsp;Germans were executed after surrendering.{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|pp=581\u2013582}} An artillery officer wrote home in April \"we should fire about a thousand rounds into every [German] town. Do them good\".{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|p=598}} At least one British battalion refused to take [[Waffen-SS]] prisoners, shooting those who surrendered; an officer of the battalion blamed this on SS \"truculence\".{{sfn|Hastings|2004|p=499}} A British battalion commander summed up the risk-averse attitude within his unit: \"At this stage of the war, no one was very keen to earn medals.\"{{sfn|Hastings|2004|p=492}} A British pilot wrote: \"It seemed a stupid time to die.\"{{sfn|Hastings|2004|p=492}} A British [[corporal]] spoke for many when he wrote \"Why don't the silly bastards give up?\"{{sfn|Atkinson|2015|p=597}} Some divisions had suffered their last fatality by mid-April.{{sfn|Hastings|2004|p=500}} The historian [[Max Hastings]] wrote \"The final Anglo-American drive across Germany offered ... many foolish little battles which wasted men's lives\".{{sfn|Hastings|2004|p=491}}\n\n===Battle for S\u00f6gel===\n[[File:Moncel and Vokes.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|right|alt=Major-General Christopher Vokes in discussion with Brigadier Robert Moncel standing in a street in S\u00f6gel on 10&nbsp;April 1945|{{center|Major-General [[Christopher Vokes]] (right) with Brigadier [[Robert Moncel]] at S\u00f6gel on 10 April 1945.}}]]\nIn early April 1945 the 4th&nbsp;Canadian (Armoured) Division, as part of [[II&nbsp;Canadian Corps]], moved out of the eastern Netherlands in the wake of the Allied crossing of the [[Rhine]] in [[Operation Plunder]]. The Canadian official history describes the circumstances as buoyant as it was recognized that the end of World War II in Europe was close.{{sfn|Stacey|1960|p=527}} On 4&nbsp;April, [[Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada (Princess Louise's)|The Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada]], part of the [[10th&nbsp;Canadian Infantry Brigade]], one of two [[brigades]] in the division,{{#tag:ref|The other battalions in the brigade were: [[The Lincoln and Welland Regiment]]; and [[The Algonquin Regiment]].{{sfn|Canadian Soldier|2019}}|group=Note}} made an assault crossing of the [[Ems (river)|Ems]] river and captured the town of [[Meppen]], suffering only one casualty. German prisoners included several 17-year-old youths with less than eight weeks of military experience.{{sfn|Stacey|1960|p=557}}\n\nThe division advanced a further {{convert|25|km}} to S\u00f6gel, which the 1st&nbsp;Battalion of [[Lake Superior Regiment|The Lake Superior Regiment (Motor)]]{{#tag:ref|The Lake Superior Regiment (Motor) was part of [[4th Canadian Armoured Brigade]] which also included: 21st Armoured Regiment ([[The Governor General's Foot Guards]]); 22nd&nbsp;Armoured Regiment ([[The Canadian Grenadier Guards]]); and 28th&nbsp;Armoured Regiment ([[The British Columbia Regiment]]).{{sfn|Canadian Soldier|2019}}|group=Note}} captured on 9&nbsp;April. The following day it repulsed several German counter-attacks before the town was declared cleared.{{sfn|Williams|1988|p=276}}{{sfn|Stacey|1960|p=558}} Some German civilians joined the fighting and were believed to have killed several Canadian soldiers. Vokes, believing the civilians needed to be taught a lesson, ordered the destruction of the centre of the town.{{sfn|Morton|2016|}} This was accomplished with several truckloads of dynamite. Vokes was aware that these actions violated the Hague Conventions and took care not to issue written instructions.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|pp=258\u2013259}} Soldiers of the division started referring to Vokes as \"The Sod of S\u00f6gel\".{{sfn|Foster|2000|page=437}} The Canadian Army official history states: {{quote|Investigation established that German civilians had taken part in this fighting and had been responsible for the loss of Canadian lives. Accordingly, as a [[reprisal]] and a warning, several houses in the centre of S\u00f6gel were ordered destroyed by the engineers to provide rubble.{{sfn|Stacey|1960|p=558}}}}\n\n==Battle for Friesoythe==\n\nThe Canadian advance continued across the [[Westphalian Lowland]], reaching the outskirts of Friesoythe, a strategic crossroads, on 13&nbsp;April. As it was early spring, the ground was sodden and heavy vehicles could not operate off the main roads.{{sfn|Stacey|1960|p=558}} This made Friesoythe, {{convert|20|mi|km|disp=flip}} west of [[Oldenburg]], on the River [[Soeste]], a potential bottleneck. If the Germans were to hold it, the bulk of the Canadians would be unable to continue their advance.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=305}} Most of the population of 4,000 had evacuated to the countryside on 11\u201312 April.{{#tag:ref|The Friesoythe Amtsgericht, or District Court, was closed on 11&nbsp; April. If the District Court ceased to function on 11&nbsp;April 1945, the evacuation of the bulk of the civilian population probably took place between 11&nbsp;and 12&nbsp;April. This was clearly a German initiative.{{sfn|Cloppenburg|2003|pp=165, 189}}{{sfn|Brockhaus|1996|p=730}}|group=Note}} Several hundred paratroopers from Battalion Raabe of the German [[7th Parachute Division (Germany)|7th&nbsp;Parachute Division]] and anti-tank guns defended the town.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=305}}{{sfn|Sirluck|1945|}} The paratroopers repelled an attack by the Lake Superior Regiment, which suffered several killed and wounded; German casualties are unknown.{{sfn|Marsh|2015|}}\n\nVokes ordered the resumption of the attack by the 1st&nbsp;Battalion, The Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders (Princess Louise's), commanded by [[Lieutenant-colonel (Canada)|Lieutenant-Colonel]] Frederick Wigle. The Argylls conducted a flanking night march and launched a dawn assault on 14&nbsp;April. The attack met only scattered resistance from a disorganized garrison, and the Argylls secured the town by 10:30. During the confused fighting, approximately 50&nbsp;German soldiers{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=257}} caught Wigle's tactical headquarters by surprise at around 08:30. A firefight broke out, resulting in the death of Wigle and several other soldiers. A rumour circulated that a local civilian had shot Wigle.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=308}}{{sfn|A&SHC archive|1945}}{{sfn|Fraser|1996|p=431}}\n\n===Destruction of Friesoythe===\nVokes was furious when he heard of Wigle's death. He wrote in his autobiography that \"a first-rate officer of mine, for whom I had a special regard and affection, and in whom I had a particular professional interest because of his talent for command, was killed. Not merely killed, it was reported to me, but sniped in the back\". Vokes wrote, \"I summoned my {{Abbr|GSO1|general staff officer}}... 'Mac,' I roared at him, 'I'm going to raze that goddam town. Tell 'em we're going to level the fucking place. Get the people the hell out of their houses first.{{'\"}}{{sfn|Foster|2000|page=437}}{{sfn|Vokes|1985|pages=194\u2013195}} Vokes's [[Staff_(military)#British_and_Commonwealth_staff|GSO1 (head of the operations staff)]], Lieutenant-Colonel Mackenzie Robinson, obeyed but convinced him to not put this order in writing or issue a proclamation to the local civilians.{{sfn|Foster|2000|page=437}}{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|pp=259, 295}} Hastings writes that the earlier incident at S\u00f6gel contributed to Vokes's fury.{{sfn|Hastings|2004|p=500}}\n\nThe Argylls had spontaneously begun to burn Friesoythe in reprisal for the death of their commander.{{sfn|Fraser|1996|pp=435\u2013437}} After Vokes had issued his order, the town was systematically set on fire with [[flamethrowers]] mounted on [[Universal Carrier|Wasp Carriers]]. In the side streets, soldiers threw petrol containers into buildings and ignited them with [[White phosphorus munitions|phosphorus grenades]]. The attack continued for over eight hours and Friesoythe was almost totally destroyed.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=308}} As the commanding officer of the 1st&nbsp;Battalion, [[The Algonquin Regiment]] later wrote, \"the raging Highlanders cleared the remainder of that town as no town has been cleared for centuries, we venture to say\".{{sfn|Cassidy|1948|p=307}} The war diary of the 4th&nbsp;Canadian Armoured Brigade records, \"when darkness fell Friesoythe was a reasonable facsimile of Dante's Inferno\".{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=309}}\n\nThe Canadian official history states that Friesoythe \"was set on fire in a mistaken reprisal\".{{sfn|Stacey|1960|p=722}} The rubble was used to reinforce the local roads for the division's tanks and heavy transport, which had been unable to move up due to the main roads near the town being badly cratered, and the smaller roads being inadequate to stand their weight.{{sfn|Rogers|1989|p=259}}{{sfn|Granatstein|2010|p=16}}\n\n===Civilian casualties and damage===\nDuring the fighting around Friesoythe and its aftermath, ten civilians from the town and another ten from the surrounding villages were killed.{{sfn|Stadt Friesoythe|2018}} There were reports of civilians lying dead in the streets.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=308}} According to one German assessment, 85\u201390 per cent of the town was destroyed during the reprisal.{{sfn|Cloppenburg|2003|p=189}} The {{Lang|de|Brockhaus Enzyklopaedie}} estimates the destruction to have been as high as 90 per cent. The town's website records that of 381{{nbsp}}houses in the town proper, 231{{nbsp}}were destroyed and another 30&nbsp;badly damaged.{{sfn|Stadt Friesoythe|2018}} A few days later, a Canadian nurse wrote home that the [[convent]] on the edge of town was the only building left standing.{{sfn|Hibbert|1985|p=84}} In the suburb of Altenoythe, 120{{nbsp}}houses and 110{{nbsp}}other buildings were destroyed.{{sfn|Stadt Friesoythe|2018}} In 2010, the author Mark Zuehlke suggested that, \"Not all of Friesoythe was burnt, but its centre was destroyed\".{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=309}}\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n{{Quote box|width=20em|align=left|quote=You should know our soldiers were kind to the children of our enemies, and kind to those in adversity. And they were, on the whole, great ambassadors for Canada.|source=Major-General Christopher Vokes in his autobiography{{sfn|Vokes|1985|p=x}}}}The Argyll's war diary made no mention of their afternoon's activity, noting in passing that \"many fires were raging\". There is no record of the deliberate destruction at division, corps or army level.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=309}} The war diary of the division's 8th&nbsp;Anti-Aircraft Regiment records \"the Argylls were attacked in that town yesterday by German forces assisted by civilians and today the whole town is being systematically razed. A stern atonement&nbsp;...\"{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=309}} The 1st&nbsp;Battalion, The Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders (Princess Louise's) were awarded the [[battle honour]] \"Friesoythe\", as were the 1st&nbsp;Battalion, The Lake Superior Regiment (Motor) and the 1st&nbsp;Battalion, [[The Lincoln and Welland Regiment]].{{sfn|Canadian Forces Heritage|2017}}\n\nOn 16&nbsp;April The Lincoln and Welland Regiment attacked [[Garrel]], {{convert|10|miles|km|disp=flip}} south-west of Friesoythe. After a German act of [[perfidy]]{{snd}}the mayor surrendered the town but the first tank to enter was destroyed by a [[Panzerfaust]]{{snd}}the battalion commander, Wigle's brother-in-law, ordered that \"every building which did not show a white flag be fired\".{{sfn|L&WR archive|1945}} Before it could be carried out, the order was countermanded and the village was spared.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|page=312}} A Canadian force was also authorized to burn down the village of [[Mittelsten]] following what the historian Perry Briddiscombe calls \"an unnamed transgression\". They were talked out of this by a Canadian engineer unit as Mittelsten's civilians were running an army sawmill.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=258}}\n\n===Post-war===\nIn early 1946 Vokes heard an appeal against the death sentence of [[Kurt Meyer]], a convicted German war criminal. Referring to his discussions about this Vokes said to the [[Vincent Massey|Canadian High Commissioner]] in London, \"I told them of S\u00f6gel and Friesoythe and of the prisoners and civilians that my troops had killed in Italy and Northwest Europe\".{{sfn|Foster|2000|page=437}} Vokes [[commutation of sentence|commuted]] the sentence to life imprisonment saying, \"There isn't a general or colonel on the Allied side that I know of who hasn't said, 'Well, this time we don't want any prisoners{{'}}\".{{sfn|Brode|1997|p=105}}\n\nThe Canadian Army official historian, Colonel [[Charles Perry Stacey|Charles Stacey]], visited Friesoythe on 15&nbsp;April. He wrote in the Canadian Army official history, which was published in 1960, that \"there is no record of how this [destruction] came about\".{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|p=309}}{{sfn|Stacey|1960|pp=558, 722}} Responding to this, the historian Mark Zuehlke wrote that there were records of the events in the war diaries of several units, but that he did not believe Stacey's vagueness was an attempt at a cover-up.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2010|p=309}} In his 1982 memoirs Stacey expanded upon the official history to comment that the only time he saw what could be considered a [[war crime]] committed by Canadian soldiers{{#tag:ref|The [[Hague Conventions of 1899 and 1907|1907 Convention Respecting the Laws and Customs of War on Land]] (Hague{{nbsp}}IV), Article{{nbsp}}23, prohibits acts that \"destroy or seize the enemy's property, unless such destruction or seizure be imperatively demanded by the necessities of war.\"{{sfn|ICRC|1907}}|group=Note}} was when\n{{quote|... at Friesoythe, the Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada&nbsp;... lost their popular commanding officer&nbsp;... as a result a great part of the town of Friesoythe was set on fire in a mistaken reprisal. This unfortunate episode only came to my notice and thus got into the pages of history because I was in Friesoythe at the time and saw people being turned out of their houses and the houses burned. How painfully easy it is for the business of \"reprisals\" to get out of hand!{{sfn|Stacey|1982|pp=163\u2013164}}}}\n\nVokes commented in his autobiography, written forty years after the event, that he had \"[a] feeling of no great remorse over the elimination of Friesoythe. Be that as it may.\"{{sfn|Morton|2016}}{{sfn|Foster|2000|page=437}} This position may have been motivated by a continued belief that the retaliatory actions were justified.{{sfn|Briddiscombe|1998|p=295}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Allied war crimes during World War II]]\n* [[List of war crimes]]\n\n==Notes, citations and sources==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Ambrose | first = Stephen E. | title = Citizen Soldiers: The U.S. Army From the Normandy Beaches to the Bulge to the Surrender of Germany | publisher = [[Simon & Schuster]] | year = 1997 | location = New York City, New York | isbn = 0-684-815257 | url = https://archive.org/details/citizensoldiers000ambr|ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book\n|last=\n|first=\n|date=\n|id= RG 24, v. 15,005\n|title=Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada War Diary\n|url=\n|location=Ottawa, ON, Canada\n|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]\n|pages=10\u201311\n|isbn=\n|author-link=\n|ref={{sfnRef|A&SHC archive|1945}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Atkinson|first=Rick|authorlink=Rick Atkinson|title=The Guns at Last Light|location=Great Britain|publisher=[[Abacus]]|date=2015|isbn=978-0-349-14048-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Briddiscombe |first1=Perry |title=Werwolf! : The History of the National Socialist Guerrilla Movement, 1944\u20131946 |date=1998 |publisher=[[University of Toronto Press]] |location=Toronto |isbn=978-0-8020-0862-6 |ref=harv |url=https://archive.org/details/werwolfhistoryof00bidd }}\n* {{Cite book |title=[[Brockhaus Enzyklop\u00e4die|Die Enzyklop\u00e4die]], 20. Aufl. V. 7 |publisher=Brockhaus |year=1996 |isbn= |location=Leipzig |ref=CITEREFBrockhaus1996}}\n* {{cite book\n  |first=Patrick\n  |last=Brode\n  |title=Casual Slaughters and Accidental Judgements: Canadian War Crimes Prosecutions, 1944\u20131948\n  |year=1997\n|location=Toronto; Buffalo\n|publisher=For Osgoode Society for Canadian Legal History by University of Toronto Press\n  |isbn=08020-4204-X\n  |ref=harv\n  |url=https://archive.org/details/casualslaughters0000brod\n  }}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.cmp-cpm.forces.gc.ca/dhh-dhp/his/ol-lo/vol-tom-3/par2/doc/ir-ri.pdf|title=''The Insignia and Linages of the Canadian Forces''. Volume 3, Part Two. \"Infantry Regiments\"|last=|first=|date=13 August 2018|website=A Canadian Forces Heritage Publication|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206053149/http://www.cmp-cpm.forces.gc.ca/dhh-dhp/his/ol-lo/vol-tom-3/par2/doc/ir-ri.pdf|archive-date=6 December 2017|access-date=|ref={{sfnRef|Canadian Forces Heritage|2017}}}}\n{{cite web | url=http://www.canadiansoldiers.com/organization/fieldforces/casf/4thdivision.htm | title=4th Canadian (Armoured) Division | publisher=Canadian Soldier | accessdate=21 November 2019|ref={{sfnRef|Canadian Soldier|2019}}}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Warpath; the Story of the Algonquin Regiment, 1939\u20131945 |last=Cassidy |first=G. L. |publisher=[[Ryerson Press]] |year=1948 |oclc=937425850 |location=Toronto |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Die Stadt Friesoythe im zwanzigsten Jahrhundert |trans-title=The town of Friesoythe in the twentieth century) |last=Cloppenburg |first=Ferdinand |location=Friesoythe |publisher=Schepers |year=2003 |language=German |isbn= 3-00-012759-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Meeting of Generals |last=Foster |first=Tony |publisher=[[iUniverse]] |year=2000 |isbn=978-0-595-13750-3 |location=San Jose; New York |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Black Yesterdays; the Argylls' War |last=Fraser |first=Robert L. |publisher=Argyll Regimental Foundation |y