s |first=Chris |publisher=[[Gallery Books]] |year=1985 |isbn=978-0-9692109-0-0 |location=Ottawa |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=The Long Left Flank: the Hard Fought Way to the Reich, 1944\u20131945 |last=Williams |first=Jeffery |year=1988 |publisher=[[Stoddart Publishing|Stoddart]] |isbn=978-0-7737-2194-4 |location=Toronto |oclc=25747884 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=On To Victory: The Canadian Liberation of the Netherlands |last=Zuehlke |first=Mark |publisher=[[Greystone Books]] |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-55365-430-8 |location=Vancouver |ref=harv}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Friesoythe, Razing of}}\n\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving Germany]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving Canada]]\n[[Category:1945 in Germany]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1945]]\n[[Category:April 1945 events]]\n[[Category:War crimes]]\n[[Category:Collective punishment]]\n[[Category:World War II crimes]]\n[[Category:Razed cities]]\n", "name_user": "117.199.95.192", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Razing_of_Friesoythe"}
{"title_page": "Offenbach-Bieber", "text_new": "{{no refs|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox German location\n|name         = Bieber \n|type         = [[Stadtteil]]\n|Town         = [[Offenbach am Main]]\n|image_photo  = Offenbach-Bieber Luftbild 004.jpg\n|image_caption  = Aerial picture of Bieber from the west\n|image_coa            = WappenOffenbach-Bieber.png\n|coordinates  = {{coord|50|05|N|08|48|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|state        = Hesse\n|region       = Darmstadt \n|district     = urban\n|elevation    = \n|area         = \n|population   = \n|population_as_of = \n|postal_code  = 63073\n|area_code    = 069\n|licence      = \n|website      = \n}}\n\n[[File:Bieberer Amulett.JPG|thumb|150px|''Bieberer Amulett'']]\n[[File:BieberFachwerk01.jpg|thumb|200px|Historical half-timbered building]]\n\n'''Bieber''' is a village of [[Hesse]], [[Germany]], with a total population of 14,797 as of 2005. Since 1938 it has been a ''[[Ortsteil|Stadtteil]]'' of [[Offenbach am Main]]. \n\n== Geography ==\nA small river, a tributary of the [[Rodau (Main)|Rodau]] called ''[[Bieber (Rodau)|Bieber]]'' flows through the village. \n\nAt the top of the hill ''Bieberer Berg'' (elevation 120 m above NHN) stands the soccer-stadium ''[[Sparda Bank Hessen Stadium|Sparda Bank Hessen Stadion]]'', formerly the ''[[Bierberer Berg Stadion|Stadion Bieberer Berg]]'', home of the soccer team ''[[Kickers Offenbach]]''.\n\n== History ==\nThe village's name is derived from the Celtic people. Bieber as such was first mentioned in 791 as ''Biberaha'' in a donation.\n\nInto the 19th century, Bieber's population was Roman Catholic. Now there is the catholic parish ''St. Nikolaus'' and a Protestant parish.\n\nIn 1938, the former municipality Bieber was merged with Offenbach.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n===Transport===\nBieber is part of the [[Frankfurt Transit|S-Bahn Rhein-Main-System]] with two [[S-Bahn]] stations: [[Offenbach-Bieber station]] is near the centre of the village and the other is in the borough of ''Bieber-Waldhof'' (3,500 Inhabitants in 2005).\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Offenbach-Bieber}}\n*[https://www.offenbach.de/leben-in-of/stadtteile-quartiersmanagement/bieber/subrubrik-bieber.php Municipal website of Offenbach, Stadtteil Bieber (German)]\n*[http://www.ngw.nl/int/dld/b/bieber2.htm Arms of Bieber]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Boroughs of Offenbach am Main|Bieber]]\n\n\n{{Hesse-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{no refs|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox German location\n|name         = Bieber \n|type         = [[Stadtteil]]\n|Town         = [[Offenbach am Main]]\n|image_photo  = Offenbach-Bieber Luftbild 004.jpg\n|image_caption  = Aerial picture of Bieber from the west\n|image_coa            = WappenOffenbach-Bieber.png\n|coordinates  = {{coord|50|05|0|N|08|48|0|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|map_type   = Germany\n|state        = Hesse\n|region       = Darmstadt \n|district     = urban\n|elevation    = \n|area         = \n|population   = \n|population_as_of = \n|postal_code  = 63073\n|area_code    = 069\n|licence      = \n|website      = \n}}\n\n[[File:Bieberer Amulett.JPG|thumb|150px|''Bieberer Amulett'']]\n[[File:BieberFachwerk01.jpg|thumb|200px|Historical half-timbered building]]\n\n'''Bieber''' is a village of [[Hesse]], [[Germany]], with a total population of 14,797 as of 2005. Since 1938 it has been a ''[[Ortsteil|Stadtteil]]'' of [[Offenbach am Main]]. \n\n== Geography ==\nA small river, a tributary of the [[Rodau (Main)|Rodau]] called ''[[Bieber (Rodau)|Bieber]]'' flows through the village. \n\nAt the top of the hill ''Bieberer Berg'' (elevation 120 m above NHN) stands the soccer-stadium ''[[Sparda Bank Hessen Stadium|Sparda Bank Hessen Stadion]]'', formerly the ''[[Bierberer Berg Stadion|Stadion Bieberer Berg]]'', home of the soccer team ''[[Kickers Offenbach]]''.\n\n== History ==\nThe village's name is derived from the Celtic people. Bieber as such was first mentioned in 791 as ''Biberaha'' in a donation.\n\nInto the 19th century, Bieber's population was Roman Catholic. Now there is the catholic parish ''St. Nikolaus'' and a Protestant parish.\n\nIn 1938, the former municipality Bieber was merged with Offenbach.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n===Transport===\nBieber is part of the [[Frankfurt Transit|S-Bahn Rhein-Main-System]] with two [[S-Bahn]] stations: [[Offenbach-Bieber station]] is near the centre of the village and the other is in the borough of ''Bieber-Waldhof'' (3,500 Inhabitants in 2005).\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Offenbach-Bieber}}\n*[https://www.offenbach.de/leben-in-of/stadtteile-quartiersmanagement/bieber/subrubrik-bieber.php Municipal website of Offenbach, Stadtteil Bieber (German)]\n*[http://www.ngw.nl/int/dld/b/bieber2.htm Arms of Bieber]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Boroughs of Offenbach am Main|Bieber]]\n\n\n{{Hesse-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Offenbach-Bieber"}
{"title_page": "Benee", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{short description|New Zealand singer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Benee\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Benee performing live at Spotify's Front Left Live playlist event in Melbourne (2019) (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Benee at [[Forum Theatre|The Forum]] in October 2019\n| birth_name       = Stella Rose Bennett<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opencorporates.com/officers/374086399|title=Stella Rose BENNETT: Director of BeneMusicc LTD (New Zealand)|website=[[OpenCorporates]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315092944/https://opencorporates.com/officers/374086399|archive-date=15 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Grey Lynn]], [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]]<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/benee-mn0003850385/biography|title=BENEE: Biography & History|last=Donelson|first=Marcy|website=[[AllMusic]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|2000|1|30|df=yes}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B78QiiXgACD/?igshid=1dpjqnrlrqdib|title=@beneemusic on Instagram: 20 \ud83e\udd0e|publisher=BENEE [verified account]|date=30 January 2020|accessdate=13 March 2020|website=Instagram}}</ref>\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>|[[indie rock]]<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>}}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| occupation       = Singer-songwriter\n| years_active     = 2017\u2013present\n| label            = [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| website          = {{url|beneemusic.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Stella Rose Bennett''' (born 30 January 2000), known professionally as '''Benee''' ({{IPAc-en|'|b|\u025b|n|i\u02d0}}, stylised '''BENEE''', formerly spelt '''Bene''') is a [[New Zealand]] singer-songwriter from [[Auckland]]. In 2019, Benee won 4 [[New Zealand Music Awards]], namely [[New Zealand Music Award for Single of the Year|Single of The Year]], [[New Zealand Music Award for Best Solo Artist|Best Solo Artist]], [[New Zealand Music Award for Breakthrough Artist of the Year|Best Breakthrough Artist]] and Best Pop Artist. She is best known for her singles \"[[Glitter (Benee song)|Glitter]]\", \"[[Soaked (song)|Soaked]]\" and \"[[Supalonely]]\" which have gained over 164 million [[Streaming media|streams]] on [[Spotify]] altogether.<!-- Use Spotify's desktop app to see stats on Benee's artist page -->\n\nBenee made her solo debut under the moniker of Bene with the 2017 single \"Tough Guy\", before gaining prominence with her 2018 single \"[[Soaked (song)|Soaked]]\", which was certified double-platinum in New Zealand. She released her debut EP, ''[[Fire on Marzz]]'', with help from producer [[Kidz in Space|Josh Fountain]] in June 2019. Her second EP, ''[[Stella & Steve]]'', was released in September 2019 and charted in the US, Canada and France as a result of the international success of the EP's final single \"[[Supalonely]]\".\n\n== Life and career ==\n\n=== 2000\u20132016: Early life ===\nStella Rose Bennett was born and raised in the suburb of [[Grey Lynn]] in [[Auckland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fashionjournal.com.au/music/get-to-know-benee/|title=Get to know Benee, if you know what's good for you|last=Sholly|first=Eliza|date=29 November 2019|website=Fashion Journal|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spinoff\">{{cite web|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/music/13-07-2019/it-was-a-bit-nuts-kind-of-mindblowing-benee-on-touring-the-world-and-stuffing-up/ |title=\u2018It was a bit nuts, mindblowing\u2019: Benee on touring the world and stuffing up |last=McAuley |first=Matthew |publisher=[[The Spinoff]]|date=14 July 2019|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> She grew up in a \"really musical\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.neckofthewoods.co.nz/word-in-the-woods/2018/7/31/revealing-bene|title=Revealing BENE|date=31 July 2018|website=Neck of The Woods|language=en-NZ|url-status=live|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> family with parents who would expose her to the catalogs of [[Radiohead]], [[Bj\u00f6rk]] and [[Groove Armada]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/national/programmes/nat-music/audio/2018731105/the-mixtape-benee|title=Six things you probably didn\u2019t know about Benee|date=24 January 2020|website=[[RNZ]]|language=en-nz|url-status=live|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/jgeg8b/benee-and-gus-dapperton-turn-breakup-blues-into-sunny-pop-on-supalonely|title=BENEE and Gus Dapperton turn breakup blues into sunny pop on Supalonely|last=Marsh|first=Ariana|date=4 February 2020|website=[[i-D]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buro247.my/culture/music/benee-interview-music-tiktok-supalonely.html|title=Benee: A melodic conversation with the 'Supalonely' singer on her music, TikTok, and more|last=Tan|first=Ronn|date=9 April 2020|website=BURO.|url-status=live|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> From the age of eight she learnt how to play the guitar as well as the saxophone, before only becoming interested in writing and recording music at the age of 17.<ref name=\":2\" /> Bennett attended a single-sex catholic school, [[St Mary's College, Auckland|St Mary's College]], where music was compulsory for four years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stmaryak.school.nz/images/Article-Attachments/Student-life/SMC-Music-Information-2020.pdf|title=St. Mary's College Music Important FAQs|website=[[St Mary's College, Auckland|St. Mary's College]]|url-status=live|access-date=3 April 2020|postscript=. '''Note:''' See ''Music Wall of Fame''}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== 2017\u20132018: Online beginnings and solo debut ===\nBenee began her music career by posting covers to [[SoundCloud]], and began making her own music in her final year of high school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/zmpwny/new-zealand-popstar-benee-|title=10 things you need to know about hazy pop superstar benee|last=Kheraj|first=Alim|date=4 June 2019|website=i-D|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> After dropping out of a communications degree at the [[Auckland University of Technology]] after two weeks, during what she called \"a quarter-life crisis\", she decided to enter the music business professionally.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=12285432|title=What you need to know about Benee, NZ music's rising star|date=14 November 2019|work=[[NZ Herald]]|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref> Her music caught the attention of [[Josh Fountain]], a producer and member of the band Leisure, with whom she worked with for both her 2017 debut single \"Tough Guy\" as well as her 2018 single \"[[Soaked (song)|Soaked]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2020/01/benee-interview|title=Meet BENEE, A Kiwi Pop Star in the Making|last=Yu|first=Eda|date=7 January 2020|website=[[Complex (website)|Complex]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sniffers.co.nz/article/auckland-teen-bene-makes-visual-debut-tough-guy|title=Auckland teen Bene makes her visual debut with \u2018Tough Guy\u2019|last=Tetlow|first=Max|date=28 February 2018|website=Sniffers|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019\u2013present: ''Fire on Marzz'' and ''Stella & Steve'' ===\nUnder the moniker of \"Bene\", Bennett released her debut EP ''[[Fire on Marzz]]'' on 28 June 2019, before later adding an \"e\" because of \"pronunciation woes\",<ref>{{Cite news|last=Fenwick|first=George|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=12245884|title=Album review: Benee, Fire on Marzz|date=11 July 2019|work=NZ Herald|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref> and copyright issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7820282/benee-interview-2019-fire-on-marzz-ep|title=Interview: BENEE Talks Debut EP 'FIRE ON MARZZ' & BENEEvision|last=Wass|first=Mike|date=2 July 2019|website=[[idolator (website)|idolator]]|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The EP, which was described by [[George Fenwick]] of ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' as \"a funky, sun-soaked record\", peaked at #13 on the [[New Zealand Albums Chart]] and at #75 on the [[Australian Albums Chart]]. The EP also earned Benee the award for [[New Zealand Music Award for Best Solo Artist|Best Solo Artist]] at the [[2019 New Zealand Music Awards]] in November 2019, where she also won awards for [[New Zealand Music Award for Single of the Year|Single of the Year]] with \"[[Soaked (song)|Soaked]]\", [[New Zealand Music Award for Breakthrough Artist of the Year|Best Breakthrough Artist]] and Best Pop Artist.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/117426344/kiwi-pop-sensation-benee-claims-four-titles-at-the-vodafone-new-zealand-music-awards|title=Kiwi pop sensation Benee claims four titles at the Vodafone New Zealand Music Awards|date=15 November 2019|website=Stuff NZ|accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nBenee's follow-up EP, ''[[Stella & Steve]]'', was released on 15 November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8543343/benee-interview-stella-steve-ep|title=Benee Interview: Singer Talks 'Stella & Steve' EP|last=Ginsberg|first=Gab|date=13 November 2019|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The EP features the single \"[[Supalonely]]\" featuring [[Gus Dapperton]], which gained international success in March 2020 after a viral dance challenge accompanied by the song spawned on the online video-sharing platform [[TikTok]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7907879/future-hit-benees-supalonely-is-absolutely-irresistible|title=Future Hit: BENEE's \"Supalonely\" Is Absolutely Irresistible|last=Wass|first=Mike|date=10 March 2020|website=[[idolator (website)|idolator]]|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/videos/benees-supalonely-is-ultra-infectious|title=BENEE's 'Supalonely' Is Ultra-Infectious|last=Murray|first=Robin|date=6 March 2020|website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> This became her second song to become viral on TikTok after \"[[Glitter (Benee song)|Glitter]]\" spawned a similar dance challenge in December 2019.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://theindustryobserver.thebrag.com/benees-glitter-is-a-dance-challenge-on-tiktok/|title=Benee\u2019s \u2018Glitter\u2019 is a dance challenge on TikTok|last=Reid|first=Poppy|date=19 December 2019|website=The Industry Observer|language=en-AU|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Benee also supported American singer-songwriter [[Conan Gray]] for nine nights of his [[Comfort Crowd Tour]] of North America during December 2019.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B2NZZJkpfSt/|title=Conan Gray on Instagram: \"HEY Y\u2019ALL \ud83d\udda4 so excited to announce that @whoisumi and @beneemusic are coming on my upcoming north american tour with me!! check out dates\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=January 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn an interview for ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'', Benee revealed that she has [[dyslexia]]. She also described her childhood experiences with songwriting:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=12216330|title=Meet Bene: The Kiwi teen taking over the charts|last=Fenwick|first=George|date=2019-03-27|access-date=2019-06-20|issn=1170-0777}}</ref> <blockquote>throughout school I struggled with writing....I liked creative writing, that was what I loved, but I was always making mistakes, and I was confined to this way that I should write....Songwriting for me was this place where I don't have to be grammatically correct. Learning the craft with [Josh Fountain], when he was sharing all his knowledge \u2013 something clicked, and I was just like, I love this. It's a great emotional outlet for me; I just love splashing what I feel on to a track.</blockquote>\n\n==Discography==\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Details\n! colspan=\"7\" scope=\"col\" | Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\"| [[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ]]<br/><ref name=\"NZBenee\">{{cite web|url=https://charts.nz/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Benee|title=Discography Benee|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]. Hung Medien|url-status=live|accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2019/07/aria-chart-watch-532/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #532|publisher=auspOp|date=6 July 2019|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/canadian-albums/2020-03-28|title=Billboard Canadian Albums Chart: March 28, 2020|website=Billboard|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|FRA]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?semaine=14?&annee=2020&categorie=Top%20Albums|title=Top Albums (Week 14, 2020)|publisher=Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|language=French|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/2020-03-28|title=Billboard 200: March 28, 2020|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Alternative Albums|US<br>Alt.]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/alternative-albums/2020-04-04|title=Alternative Albums: April 4, 2020|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Heatseekers Albums|US<br>Heat.]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/heatseekers-albums/2020-03-21|title=Heatseekers Albums: March 21, 2020|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Fire on Marzz]]''\n|\n* Released: 28 June 2019\n* Label: [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n* Formats: [[Music download|Digital download]], [[Streaming services|streaming]]\n| 13 || 75 \n|\u2014\n|\u2014|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n* [[Recorded Music New Zealand|RMNZ]]: Gold<ref>{{cite web|title=NZ Top 40 Albums Chart |date=18 January 2020 |url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=4806 |publisher=Recorded Music NZ|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Stella & Steve]]''\n|\n* Released: 15 November 2019\n* Label: Republic\n* Formats: Digital download, streaming\n| 19 || \u2014 \n|91\n|173|| 138 || 5 || 2\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"16\" style=\"font-size:90%\" | \"&mdash;\" denotes releases that did not chart.\n|}\n\n===Compilation albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Details\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''Fire on Marzz / Stella & Steve''\n|\n* Released: 14 February 2020<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marbecks.